<paper id="1543503103"><title>Another Birthday Attack</title><year>1986</year><authors><author org="(IBM Research)" id="2037645014">Don Coppersmith</author></authors><n_citation>47</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1996360405</reference><reference>2094301052</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-39799-X_2</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.53411">Block cipher</keyword><keyword weight="0.58036">Message authentication code</keyword><keyword weight="0.43254">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43784">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.54867">Digital signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.7195">Birthday attack</keyword><keyword weight="0.69212">Length extension attack</keyword><keyword weight="0.43296">Iterated function</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We show that a meet-in-the-middle attack can successfully defraud the Davies-Price message authentication scheme. Their scheme used message blocks in an iterated encipherment of an initial block, and it went through the message blocks twice, in order to prevent just such a "birthday" attack.</abstract></paper>